    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-01-27T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-01-27T11:00:00-05:00" n="9"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d9">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">825.5151/136: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Chile</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Sevier</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Santiago</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-01-27T12:00:00-04:00"
                            >January 27, 1934—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 1:10 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>11. Your telegram No. 14, January 25, noon. The Chilean Government has been
                    requested to supply the official estimates for exchange and has promised to do
                    so as soon as possible. In the meantime reference is made to page 2, enclosure
                    2, despatch No. 25, December 27th,<note n="3" xml:id="d9fn3">
                        <ref target="frus1933v05#pg_151">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1933, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">v</hi>, p. 151</ref>.</note> containing estimates
                    of exchange availabilities for 1933. These indicate, in millions gold pesos of 6
                    pence: <pb facs="0075" n="9" xml:id="pg_9"/>
                    <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>Total exchange created 181.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>Segregated through compensation agreements 42, composed of nitrate
                            blockage 18, and blockage other products 24.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>And foreign amounts available in free market 139. From this must be
                            deducted an estimated 20 representing exchange for Government expenses
                            abroad and for imports of certain non-American prime necessities. Thus
                            there was available in the free market approximately 119.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>Your paragraph number 2. The Department’s opinion that a solution might be found
                    if accessibility to the free exchange market is limited to countries not having
                    compensation agreements has been conveyed to the Foreign Office which has again
                    expressed satisfactory assurances on this point.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Sevier</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
